## 2 Background

Gradient-based Bi-level Optimization.Within deep learning applications, the model concerned with optimizing over \(\bm{\theta}\) as presented in (1) typically constitutes deep neural networks. The optimal parameters of such networks are not explicitly accessible and are estimated through iterative procedures. Consequently, the primal problem of bi-level optimization in (1) is approximately reformulated as follows:

\[\min_{\bm{\phi}\in\Phi}\;h(\bm{\phi}):=f(\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi }),\bm{\phi}),\] (2) \[\mathrm{where}\;\;\bm{\theta}_{0}(\bm{\phi})=\bm{\Omega}_{0}( \bm{\phi}),\;\;\bm{\theta}_{t}(\bm{\phi})=\bm{\Omega}_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t-1}( \bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})\in\Theta,\;\;t=1,\ldots,T,\]

where \(\Phi\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{N}\), \(\Theta\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{M}\) are the parameter spaces; \(T\), commonly called the unrolled depth, denotes the number of inner optimization steps for approximating \(\bm{\theta}^{*}(\bm{\phi})\); \(\bm{\Omega}_{0}:\mathbb{R}^{N}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{M}\) specifies the initialization of the inner optimization, and \(\bm{\Omega}_{t}:\Theta\times\Phi\rightarrow\Phi\) delineates the transition dynamics of the inner optimization at timestep \(t\). In particular, for gradient descent, \(\bm{\Omega}_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t-1}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})=\bm{\theta}_{t-1}- \eta_{t}\nabla_{\bm{\theta}}\bm{\theta}(\bm{\theta}_{t-1},\bm{\phi})\), where \(\eta_{t}\) denotes the step size at timestep \(t\).

To optimize \(\bm{\phi}\) using a first-order method, it is necessary to estimate the meta gradient \(\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}h\), which can be further decomposed according to the chain rule:

\[\underbrace{\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}h(\bm{\phi})}_{\text{meta gradient}}= \underbrace{\frac{\partial f(\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})}{\partial \bm{\theta}_{T}}\frac{d\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi})}{d\bm{\phi}}}_{\text{implicit gradient}}+\underbrace{\frac{\partial f(\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})}{ \partial\bm{\phi}}}_{\text{explicit gradient}}.\] (3)

The computation of meta-gradient poses a significant challenge, primarily due to the need for efficient approximation of the implicit gradient. This task is complicated by the recursive dependency of \(\bm{\theta}_{T}\) on \(\bm{\phi}\). To surmount this challenge, a variety of gradient-based bi-level optimization algorithms have been developed, as extensively reviewed recently in [73]. These algorithms can be fundamentally categorized into three types based on their approach to meta-gradient approximation: _Gradient Unrolling_ (GU), _Implicit Function_ (IF), and _Value Function_ (VF). Recent innovations such as truncated RGU (TRGU) [60] and Hessian-Free approaches [76; 75; 9], which are predicated on GU and IF methodologies respectively, have introduced significant biases in their approximations to accommodate the computational constraints of large-scale scenarios. In the subsequent paragraph, we furnish a concise overview of GU-based approaches, addressing their non-constant memory issues in large-scale applications. Extended discussions on the remaining methods are reserved for Appendix B.

Gradient Unrolling.The core idea behind GU [17; 16; 40; 60] entails unrolling the inner optimization into an expansive computational graph, followed by the employment of automatic differentiation (AD) techniques for the iterative computation of gradients.

_Forward Gradient Unrolling_ (FGU) [17; 16] computes the meta gradient using the following forward recursive formula, starting from \(\bm{Z}_{0}=\frac{d\bm{\Omega}_{0}(\bm{\phi})}{d\bm{\phi}}\):

\[\underbrace{\frac{d\bm{\theta}_{t}(\bm{\phi})}{d\bm{\phi}}}_{\bm{Z}_{t}}= \underbrace{\frac{\partial\bm{\Omega}_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t-1}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{ \phi})}{\partial\bm{\theta}_{t-1}}\frac{d\bm{\theta}_{t-1}(\bm{\phi})}{d\bm{ \phi}}}_{\bm{Z}_{t}}+\underbrace{\frac{\partial\bm{\Omega}_{t}(\bm{\theta}_{t-1 }(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})}{\partial\bm{\phi}}}_{\bm{B}_{t}},\;t=1,\ldots,T,\] (4)_Reverse Gradient Unrolling_ (RGU) [46; 16], instead of the employment of explicit recursive formulas of \(\bm{Z}_{T}\), focuses on the implicit recursive formulas of \(\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}h\):

\[\nabla_{\bm{\phi}}h(\bm{\phi})= \underbrace{\frac{\partial f(\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi} )}{\partial\bm{\theta}_{T}}}_{\bm{d}_{T}}\underbrace{\frac{d\bm{\theta}_{T}( \bm{\phi})}{d\bm{\phi}}}_{\bm{Z}_{T}}+\underbrace{\frac{\partial f(\bm{\theta} _{T}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})}{\partial\bm{\phi}}}_{\bm{e}_{T}}\] (5) \[= \bm{d}_{T}\bm{Z}_{T}+\bm{c}_{T}\underbrace{\frac{(d)}{d_{T}}\bm{A }_{T}}_{\bm{d}_{T-1}}\bm{Z}_{T-1}+\underbrace{\bm{d}_{T}\bm{B}_{T}+\bm{c}_{T}} _{\bm{c}_{T-1}}=\cdots=\bm{d}_{0}\bm{Z}_{0}+\bm{c}_{0}.\]

The corresponding reverse recursive formulas can thus be summarized as

\[\bm{c}_{t-1}=\bm{c}_{t}+\bm{d}_{t}\bm{B}_{t},\quad\bm{d}_{t-1}=\bm{d}_{t}\bm{ A}_{t},\quad t=T,\ldots,1.\] (6)

**Weakness (GU): Non-Constant Memory**. Both GU approaches exhibit a non-constant memory overhead, which constrains their utility in large-scale scenarios. The forward recursive formulas in (4) revolve around the Jacobian matrix product, demanding \(\mathcal{O}(MN)\) space consumption. The reverse recursive formulas in (6) necessitate the storage of the entire trajectory of the inner optimization \(\bm{\theta}_{0:T}\) for backward computation, thereby imposing a memory requirement of \(\mathcal{O}(TM)\). These requirements are often impractical for large-scale bi-level optimization, when \(\bm{\phi}\) and \(\bm{\theta}\) are of high dimension and a significant unrolled depth is required.

**Forward Gradient.** Forward-mode automatic differentiation (forward-mode AD) has been applied to a variety of research fields, including the training of recurrent neural networks [70], the computation of Hessian vector products [50], etc. However, the computation of the true gradient via forward-mode AD requires the full Jacobian, which is typically too costly to compute.

To solve this, forward gradient learning [69; 4; 63; 4; 56], built upon forward-mode AD, was proposed. Forward gradient methods update parameters based on the directional gradient along a random perturbation direction for backpropagation-free training. More formally, given a differentiable function \(h:\mathbb{R}^{N}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\), the gradient for a given input \(\bm{\phi}\in\mathbb{R}^{N}\) can be approximated as

\[\hat{\nabla}h(\bm{\phi})=\nabla h(\bm{\phi})\bm{v}\bm{v}^{T},\] (7)

where \(\bm{v}\sim p(\bm{v})\) is a \(N\)-dimensional multivariate random variable, satisfying \(\mathbb{E}[\bm{v}\bm{v}^{T}]=\mathbf{I}\). Common choices of the distribution of \(\bm{v}\) include Rademacher \(\bm{v}\sim\mathrm{Unif}(\{-1,1\}^{N})\), Gaussian \(\bm{v}\sim\mathcal{N}(\bm{0},\bm{I})\), and uniform distribution over a set of normalized orthogonal coordinates \(\bm{v}\sim\mathrm{Unif}(\{\sqrt{N}\bm{e}_{i}\}_{1:N})\). For any given \(\bm{\phi}\), \(\hat{\nabla}h(\bm{\phi})\) is an unbiased estimator of \(\nabla h(\bm{\phi})\), as \(\mathbb{E}[\hat{\nabla}h(\bm{\phi})]=\mathbb{E}[\nabla h(\bm{\phi})\bm{v}\bm{ v}^{T}]=\nabla h(\bm{\phi})\mathbb{E}[\bm{v}\bm{v}^{T}]=\nabla h(\bm{\phi}) \mathbf{I}=\nabla h(\bm{\phi})\). Despite the unbiasedness of \(\hat{\nabla}h\), the dimension-dependent variance of the estimated gradient with a single direction impedes the scaling-up to high-dimensional problems. In practice, Monte Carlo gradient estimation can be used via averaged forward gradients over multiple random directions to reduce the variance.

## 3 (FG)\({}^{2}\)U: Forward Gradient Unrolling with Forward Gradient

We aim to circumvent the memory overhead issues associated with forward gradient unrolling (FGU) as discussed in Section 2. We begin by examining the forward gradient of \(h\) at \(\bm{\phi}\),

\[\hat{\nabla}h(\bm{\phi})=\nabla h(\bm{\phi})\bm{v}\bm{v}^{T} \stackrel{{\eqref{eq:f_eq_eq_1}}}{{=}}(\bm{d}_{T}\bm{Z}_{T}\bm{v}+ \bm{c}_{T}\bm{v})\bm{v}^{T},\] (8)

where \(\bm{v}\sim p(\bm{v})\) is a \(N\)-dimensional multivariate random variable, satisfying \(\mathbb{E}[\bm{v}\bm{v}^{T}]=\mathbf{I}\). We follow the idea of FGU introduced in Section 2 to compute \(\bm{Z}_{T}\bm{v}\). By multiplying both sides of (4) by \(\bm{v}\) on the right, we can obtain the recursive formulas for \(\bm{Z}_{t}\bm{v}\) as

\[\bm{Z}_{0}\bm{v}=\bm{B}_{0}\bm{v};\quad\bm{Z}_{t}\bm{v}=\bm{A}_{t}\bm{Z}_{t-1} \bm{v}+\bm{B}_{t}\bm{v},\ \ t=1,\ldots,T.\] (9)

The revised recursive formulas in (9) facilitate the tracking of a \(M\)-dimensional vector \(\bm{Z}_{t}\bm{v}\), rather than full Jacobian \(\bm{Z}_{t}\) of size \(M\times N\), throughout the forward pass. The stochastic estimation in (8) is unbiased, adhering to the properties of forward gradient methods. To reduce the variance, we use Monte Carlo estimate via averaged forward gradients over _b i.i.d._ random directions:

\[\hat{\nabla}h(\bm{\phi})=\frac{1}{b}\sum_{i=1}^{b}\nabla h(\bm{\phi})\bm{v}_{i} \bm{v}_{i}{}^{T}=\frac{1}{b}\sum_{i=1}^{b}(\bm{d}_{T}\bm{Z}_{T}\bm{v}_{i}+\bm{c }_{T}\bm{v}_{i})\bm{v}_{i}{}^{T}.\] (10)

We call this algorithm **(FG)2U**, as an abbreviation of **F**orward **G**radient **U**nrolling with **F**orward **G**radient. The algorithm is summarized in Appendix A as Algorithm 1.

