Another idea for computing the implicit gradient is to utilize the implicit function theorem (IFT) [30]. Suppose that the inner optimality \(\nabla\bm{\sigma}g(\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})\approx 0\) is approximately achieved by sufficient inner optimization steps. If \(g\) is second-order differentiable, by applying the implicit function theorem and taking the first-order derivative of \(\bm{\phi}\),

\[\frac{\partial^{2}g(\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})}{\partial\bm{\theta} _{T}^{2}}\frac{d\bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi})}{d\bm{\phi}}+\frac{\partial^{2}g( \bm{\theta}_{T}(\bm{\phi}),\bm{\phi})}{\partial\bm{\theta}_{T}\partial\bm{ \phi}}\approx 0.\] (23)Then, if the Hessian is further assumed to be invertible, the meta gradient can be approximated as

